<a target="_blank" href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=91891">Stuff a Broken Down Old Mage Uses</a></p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub6.ezboard.com/uayanlaxev.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Ayanla Xev</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 2<br> <font color=#333333>(10/7/02 7:49:59 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm32.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=361.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: Ideas</span><hr size=1> It's not that I want root so much as I want some method of not being slaughtered immediately (or gating) if I'm caught without a pet up. I would just like the option to run through an area and not have to decide on defense or invisibility.<br>
<br>
If I'm running through an area invis and something sees through, or it drops (rare since I have the fixed duration invis), it is silly that I have zero options aside from running or gating. I've tried the &quot;channel through&quot; method, and that didn't work so well *grin* I have kited mobs around and killed them without a pet but it's rare that actually works since most of our nukes have a rather long cast time and the mob is on me before I've finished casting. Generally if something sees through my invisibility I either gate or train the nearest zone. I HATE having to train an area because I have no other option aside from gating back to my bind (which is almost always nexus)<br>
<br>
I don't want to be a wizard, I thought that was pretty clear from most of my suggestions, since 90 percent of them revolve around our pet. I like being a pet class, but by the same token I do not feel that should mean I have no means of defense. The idea of the utility pet was thrown up when I was talking with my husband one night. I agree that traditional root is not within Verant's vision of a mage, and I understand how it would throw a significant advantage to the chain pet people, but I do not feel the &quot;utility pet&quot; root would give us any significant advantage other than the ability to maybe not train a zone line.<br>
<br>
Explain to me why Necromancers, the other int caster pet class, have Root, Snare, Feign, Harmshield, Shadow Step, and Gate and we have Gate. I've heard the reasoning of &quot;well our pets are stronger&quot; and quite frankly that doesn't cut it with me. I'm not talking about a measure of defense I could use when my pet is up, I'm talking about a measure of defense for situations where my pet is not up. I do not feel that would give us a significant advantage, and I'm not even asking for a method that is guaranteed, just a shot at defending myself is all I ask for.<br>
<br>
Pure caster wise let's look at defense (not counting gate)<br>
<br>
Shaman<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
<br>
Druid<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Snare: 2.25 second cast<br>
<br>
Cleric<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Stun: several, various cast times, shortest is 1 second<br>
Divine Aura: 1 second cast<br>
<br>
Enchanter<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Stuns: lots, various cast times, shortest is 1 second<br>
Rune: Longer cast but can be put up ahead of time<br>
Mez: lots, various cast times, but short<br>
<br>
Necromancer<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Feign Death: 1.5 second cast<br>
Harmshield: 1 second cast<br>
Shadowstep: 1 second cast<br>
Darkness line: Various cast times, but relatively short<br>
<br>
Wizard:<br>
Root: 2 second cast<br>
Shadowstep: 1 second cast<br>
Snare: 2.5 second cast<br>
<br>
Magician:<br>
Pet: 10 second cast<br>
<br>
